title: For Sale:  Tula Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
The bore is very clean and bright with good rifling. The stock looks to have had a repair done around where the pu scope mount would have been, could be an ex-sniper stock or maybe just a regular arsenal repair. This rifle is a ex-sniper though, during the Soviet refurbishment program the rifle was removed from sniper service and the scope mount holes were welded over and ground flush (done by the Soviets, not me), though you can still see them on the inside of the receiver. After the war the Soviets converted many of their snipers back into standard infantry rifles simply because they had too many sniper rifles and there was a high cost to maintaining the optics.

title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant - 1925 Izhevsk MO Double Date (Hex Receiver)
postcontent:
For sale is my 1925 Izhevsk MO Double date (1925/42) Mosin Nagant. I got this one in part because of the uncommon MO /42 date (42 is the earliest known MO second date). 

While it is a '20s era Mosin with some neat and uncommon stamps, I do call this one the swamp rat. Some of the metal on the barrel shank and receiver had pitting that the soviets blued over during refurb, which gives it a very odd texture. The "pitting" is very shallow and does not in any way make the rifle dangerous or unsafe. It might be blood pitting, might not. Looks like there could be a pitted thumb print possibly on the rear sight. 

The rifle has likely seen some really hard times during the wars. The stock similarly looks as thought it's seen some tough times as the shellac is cracking, peeling and flaking. The wood itself is in good condition, just the shellac placed on the rifles during refurbishment is at issue. 

That being said, this one is so ugly it's beautiful but maybe you just have to really appreciate the Mosin to see it that way... This rifle was refurbed at the 5th Grau arsenal in Alatyr Russia.

I'm selling part of my Mosin Nagant M91\30 collection to help fund another interesting gun. Sales only to Washington residents, must show proof of age and sign a bill of sale stating your legally allowed to own a firearm.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson 38/44 Outdoorsman
postcontent:
The gun is a Smith & Wesson 38/44 Outdoorsman Pre-23. Model of 1950.
There is a touch of bluing wear on each side of the muzzle, and a slight scratch near the logo. But overall, the finish is excellent.
Very tight with a very smooth trigger. Slight turn line on the cylinder.
Generally, I would say it looks better in person. Sometimes the flash washes out the detail and luster. It had some plastic target grip on it when I acquired it, and some people who have shot it like those grips, but they feel too big to me. I recently spent $150 to get a nice set of period correct N frame magna grips.
This is a very collectible gun in excellent condition,  but I will say it probably could not be considered a true high end collectors piece, as I do not have the original box, tools or matching numbered grips. Those gun go for up to or over $2000, but mine is still a nice example of a very rare gun with an excellent original finish. The gun dates to 1955 or 56, and shoots great.  Probably the most accurate handgun I own. 6-1/2" barrel. Target trigger shoe.

postcontent:
This is for the stock only. The rifle is not for sale.This is an improved Romanian wire side folding stock. If you are familiar with this type of stock you will know that it's downsides are the short length of pull and no cheekpiece for a proper cheek weld.
